NSF?s Critical Resilient Interdependent Infrastructure Systems and Processes (CRISP) annual solicitation, called RIPS (Resilient Interdependent Infrastructure Processes and Systems) in its initial year, was first announced in 2013. The solicitation aimed to enhance and improve scientific knowledge in the areas of complex, interconnected and interdependent infrastructure systems of physical, cyber and human components. This CRISP/RIPS Grantees Workshop was held on December 5-6, 2018 on the grounds of the George Mason University in Arlington, Virginia. The Workshop contributed to the enhancement and improvement of scientific engineering and education activities through lectern presentations, a workshop-wide poster session, keynote lecture, a panel giving the perspectives of federal and nongovernmental agencies related to water, energy and transportation lifelines, organized discussions on several important topics for the CRISP area, discussion about how to create a long-lasting resilience community in which the grantees (leading to The Resilience Community with URL: resilience.vse.gmu.edu) would continue to participate past the end of the CRISP program, and ideas for a joint book. Attendees included faculty, graduate and post-doctoral students, full-time researchers, personnel from the National Science Foundation, U.S. Environmental Protection Agency, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST), the Transportation Research Board, and various other agencies and governmental and nongovernmental institutions.

            Aligned with the CRISP solicitation, the specific aims of the workshop were to:

(1)   Enable the sharing of research developments and findings from funded CRISP/RIPS projects;

(2)   Promote interactions among awardees, including students and postdoctoral fellows;

(3)   Foster the creation of new interdisciplinary approaches;

(4)   Enhance and strengthen the resilience and socio-technical systems community; and

(5)   Develop novel ideas and new collaborations.

To realize the workshop goals in the areas of disseminating technical achievements, developing new interdisciplinary ideas and interdisciplinary approaches, and building community, a variety of means for delivering and understanding technical content, along with networking and collaboration-building activities, were proposed. The first day of this two-day workshop focused primarily on the sharing of technical findings between CRISP/RIPS teams, while the second day focused on generating new ideas and discussing future work and community activities. Six organized discussion sessions were held on Day-2, each with a lead or pair of leads, notetaker and Mason Liaison: (1) Water, Water, Water; (2)  Extreme Scenarios &amp; Cross-Hazard Insights; (3) Disadvantaged Populations and Locales; (4) Modeling and Calibrating Human Behavior Models; (5) Human-Computer Interactions; and (6) Ethical Dimensions. Session chairs were instructed to hold an interactive session with open dialogue and were encouraged to have the session members break out into working groups. At the end, they were asked to supply their notes and a single PowerPoint slide with key takeaways that were later presented in a workshop-wide session.

